ators","title":"Average Attributable Fraction and Other Relevant Social Sciences Indicators","text":"SocialFacts brings tool produce easily multiple indicators commonly used social sciences : - Odds Ratio, p.value CI - Average Marginal Effects, CI - cramer’s V table, check correlation categorical variables - gt table Yule’s Q value compute vars_dep argument. - new tool called Average Attributable Fraction, described Ferguson al. : use original graphPAF library, facilitate ’s use produce table resume tools one place.","code":""},{"path":"https://geminy3.github.io/SocialFacts/index.html","id":"installation","dir":"","previous_headings":"","what":"Installation","title":"Average Attributable Fraction and Other Relevant Social Sciences Indicators","text":"can install development version SocialFacts like : install via CRAN :","code":"devtools::install_github(\"Geminy3/SocialFacts\") install.packages(\"SocialFacts\")"},{"path":"https://geminy3.github.io/SocialFacts/index.html","id":"example","dir":"","previous_headings":"","what":"Example","title":"Average Attributable Fraction and Other Relevant Social Sciences Indicators","text":"basic example shows solve common problem:","code":"library(SocialFacts) ## basic example code  ### Fit a logistic model model <- glm(var_dep ~ some + var + you + have, data = data, family = binomial(...))  ### You can check the correlation between your categorical data get_cramer(var = c(\"var_1\", \"var_2\"), metric = 'cramer', data = data)  ### To compute and store the AAF resAAF <- get_AAF(model = model, nvar = 3, vars_dep = \"var_dep\", data = data)  ### To get the summary table resume_tab <- result_tab(result_tab(model = model, var_ref = \"var_dep\", var_names = c(\"var_1\", \"var_2\"),                        res_AAF = resAAF$res, data = data)  ### To view the table resume_tab  ### To export the table resume_tab |>   gtsave(filename = \"~/the/path/to/store/it/TAB_RECAP.png\", expand = 10)"},{"path":"https://geminy3.github.io/SocialFacts/ref